{
  "Question": "<p>I came across an exercise in which we are asked to prove the identity:</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_454\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"{2n\\choose n}=\\sum_{k=0}^{n}{n\\choose k}^{2}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mfrac linethickness=\"0pt\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>n</mi> </mrow> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <munderover> <mo largeop=\"true\" movablelimits=\"false\" symmetric=\"true\">\u2211</mo> <mrow> <mi>k</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> <mi>n</mi> </munderover> <msup> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mfrac linethickness=\"0pt\"> <mi>n</mi> <mi>k</mi> </mfrac> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span></p> <p>The exercise gives the hint:</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_455\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\left(1+x\\right)^{2n}=\\left[(1+x)^{n}\\right]^{2}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>n</mi> </mrow> </msup> <mo>=</mo> <msup> <mrow> <mo>[</mo> <msup> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> <mi>n</mi> </msup> <mo>]</mo> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math></span></p> <p>It's not too difficult to use the hint to prove the identity (the expressions in the identity are the coefficients of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_456\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"x^{n}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <msup> <mi>x</mi> <mi>n</mi> </msup> </math></span> in the respective expansions of the expressions in the hint, which of course must be the same number), but I was wondering whether there is a neater <em>equivalent-counting</em> interpretation...</p> <p>It's clear that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_457\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"{2n\\choose n}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mfrac linethickness=\"0pt\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>n</mi> </mrow> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span> is the number of ways in which we can choose half the elements in a set (where this is possible): how can we interpret <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_458\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\sum_{k=0}^{n}{n\\choose k}^{2}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <munderover> <mo largeop=\"true\" movablelimits=\"false\" symmetric=\"true\">\u2211</mo> <mrow> <mi>k</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> <mi>n</mi> </munderover> <msup> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mfrac linethickness=\"0pt\"> <mi>n</mi> <mi>k</mi> </mfrac> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math></span> equivalently?</p>",
  "Title": "Is there a simple combinatoric interpretation of this identity?",
  "Tags": "combinatorics,binomial-coefficients"
}